Date:    Fri, 08 Oct 93 04:36:54 -0400
From:    "Nick FitzGerald" <CCTR132@csc.canterbury.ac.nz>
Subject: Re: Companion (or spawning) viral programs (CVP)

Much as I hesitate to criticize Rob, some of his comments in a recent
posting were so far off-beam I wondered whether he actually has a PC to
test things on!   8-)  8-)

In VIRUS-L Volume 6, Issue 127 Rob Slade wrote:

[good description of DOS execution precedence deleted]
> The answer is built in to the operating system.  There are actually
> four levels of programming to check for.  First, a search is made
> for an "internal" command of the command interpreter.  If that
> succeeds, that command is run.  Thus, under MS-DOS, no program named
> DIR.COM will ever be run.  ...

Wrong!!

Totally!!!!!

Try running \dir on a DOS system -without- a dir.bat, .exe or .com in
the path.

"Bad command or filename"

- --whoops!!   8-)

> ... (Alright, unless you specify the full
> file name.  Don't be picky.)  ...

Wrong again!!

(Bad day Rob ??)   8-)

Copy a .com (or .exe for that matter) file which has an obvious but
harmless consequence to a dir on your path (or to the current dir) as
DIR.COM.  Try executing the command "dir.com".  The DOS internal dir
command will run.  (I concede that Rob -may- have meant "specify the
full -path-", in which case he is correct--see above!).

Another test.  Copy two different .exe's or .com's to TEST.EXE and
TEST.COM in the current dir.  Try executing the command "test.exe".

The program copied to TEST.COM will run.

The lessons?

COMMAND.COM checks -first- for a path in the command string, --and-- it
- -ignores- whether you have a filename extension on the command or not.

> ...  If the search does not succeed, the
> computer looks for a file with that filename and a COM extension,
> then an EXE extension, then a BAT extension.  At each stage, if the
> search succeeds, the file is run; if it fails, it goes to the next
> level.  Thus, in MS-DOS, COM takes precedence over EXE, which takes
> precedence over bAT.

As I'm here, I'll mention this again.  Those with a bent to hacking
COMMAND.COM might like to look for the string "COMEXEBAT" and modifying
it.  If you replace, say, the "EXE" part with "exe" (and reboot!) none
of your .exe's will run from the command line (COMMAND.COM uppercases
file names in directory entries and does a case sensitive comparison
against its internal list--a similar trick can be used to disable any
internal command such as dir, vol, set, path, etc, etc).  Alternatively,
you may want to change the precedence order to, say, "BATEXECOM" or
change the file extension for .exe's with say "COMEZEBAT" (remember to
rename all your .exe's to .eze!!).

Don't even ask about how batch processing works!    8-)

Later,

