Date:    Thu, 07 Oct 93 20:55:21 -0400
From:    "Steve Bonds (007" <sbonds@jarthur.Claremont.EDU>
Subject: Re: Tumbling Chars Virus (PC)

gintis@econs.umass.edu (HERBERT GINTIS) writes:

>	My wife, who is barely computer literate, told me to come
>quick, all the letters on the screen tumbled down. Sure enough, I came
>and there was a litter of broken characters on the bottom three lines
>of the screen! I rebooted and everything was okay. Is this some sort
>of virus? If so, it's cute unless it gets dangerous later!

This is the classic symptom of the Cascade family of viruses.  However, the
activation of the virus is very rarely seen since it is supposed to activate
only in the fall of 1988 by the computer's system clock.  This leads me to
suspect that someone is using one of the non-viral "joke" programs that
simulate this effect, without actually duplicating themselves.  Imitations
of Cascade are very common, since the falling letters are so unique.

To be sure it is not the real Cascade virus, you should get hold of a copy
of F-prot via FTP.  Turn your computer off and reboot from a clean diskette.
(Your original DOS disk is a good one to use.)  Unzip F-prot (preferably
using a fresh, new copy of your unzip program) and scan your hard disk.  If
F-prot turns up nothing, check your AUTOEXEC.BAT file for programs that
you did not add-- one of them could be the joke program.  F-prot may even
find it since it does scan for a few of the common "joke" programs.

To help protect yourself in the future, you should install the VIRSTOP.EXE
program that comes with F-prot as part of your CONFIG.SYS.  This will help
keep your computer virus-free, by notifying you before a program infected
with a known virus can be run.

