Date:    Fri, 08 Oct 93 20:23:25 +0000
From:    bontchev@news.informatik.uni-hamburg.de (Vesselin Bontchev)
Subject: Re: "Stone virus problem" (PC)

OS R & D (ksaj@pcscav.com) writes:

> The Stoned virus most certainly DOES infect the boot sectors of logical
> drives.  As soon as you access the drive (in this case, probably drive
> D:), it will be infected.

NONSENSE! If you don't have the correct knowledge yourself, at least
try not to mislead the other people.

ALL variants of Stoned infect the MBR of the PHYSICAL disk ONLY.
Almost all of them (I'm tempted to say ALL of them) infect the first
physical hard disk ONLY. They usually (I'm tempted to say ALWAYS) do
that ONLY when loaded from a floppy. Almost all of them infect only
floppies in the first physical ploppy disk drive. NO Stoned variant
will ever infect logical drive D:.

What you may refer to is that on computers that use compressed
volumes, the first physical disk APPEARS to be logical drive D:. But
the Stoned viruses infect it at boot time, when it is still physical
drive 80h and nothing else.

> WARNING:  Do not use FDISK/MBR for this.

Just the opposite; FDISK/MBR almost always disinfects correctly the
Stoned viruses. Even, with most of them (and certainly with the most
widespread variant), you can do this with the virus active in memory
and the virus will not reinfect the disk - because it does this only
at boot time. Nevertheless, such practice (letting the virus active in
memory) is strongly discouraged.

> In some situations it will simply delete the partition.

FDISK/MBR will not work only with some encrypted variants of Stoned
(like some members of the Empire group), which either encrypt or
overwrite the whole MBR, including the partition table.

Regards,
Vesselin
