Paul James King (pak@aber.ac.uk) writes:

> We have a machine here infected with a variant of the
> Beijing Virus (according to Visionsoft Smartscan).

> How the hell do we get rid of it ?

The Beijing virus (or, more exactly, the Stoned.June_4th.* viruses) is
a Stoned variant and as such infects the MBR of the first physical
hard disk. Try booting from a write-protected uninfected MS-DOS 5.0
(or later) system diskette and execute the command FDISK/MBR. This
should remove the virus from your hard disk.

> The virus is causing the machine to come up with the
> following error message:

> 	General failure reading drive a:

> MacAfee's Viruscan program abandons the scan due to the
> above error.

Drive A: is a 3.5" high-capacity drive, right? The error is caused
because the virus trashes the BPB in the boot sector. I think that the
latest version of F-Prot can get around this problem by accessing the
floppy in a physical level, so you should try it. I'm not sure that it
will work, though.

> Nortons Disk Editor also fails with the General failure message.

Try starting it in Maintnance mode (option /m) and read the floppy as
physical sectors.

Regards,
Vesselin
